review.reviewBody: I'm thoroughly impressed at ORs first foray into the MTB scene, and this jersey is no exception! I've used this for trail rides, gravel rides, and even a chilly trainer sesh in the garage, and whoa, does this thing breathe insanely well! It definitely isn't the most lightweight option in my closet, but it's also not something I will stop reaching for until temps start skyrocketing towards triple digits. The fabric is super soft to the touch, and the goggle wipe is a nice addition so I can definitely see myself throwing this on under a chest protector for warm weather days at the bike park. One caveat is that you'll need to size up if you prefer a baggier fit. I'm a medium/large across the board in OR, and the large in this jersey was a bit of a slimmer fit than I prefer.
review.name: Solid midweight longsleeve

review.reviewBody:
The baker bib is honestly one of the best, most durable bibs you will find out there. 
I use these daily coaching over 100+ days on the hill in the US, and 60+ in South America and they still have not tear, still hold their water repellency, and are incredibly comfortable.
Good breathability, plenty of ventilation zippers, and many pockets. Truly a must for your quiver.
In comparison to the regular baker bib, the perm baker bib is lighter, and its material more water resistant. In my opinion, I like the perm baker bib over the regular one in terms of comfortability.
review.name: Baker Rules

review.reviewBody: I bought these with ski touring in mind, but they are definitely built well enough for rough in bounds wear. They are now my daily drivers for any activity on two planks. These fit just a bit smaller than other bibs of the same size I have owned. Not enough that i would size up, but i am pretty slim. If you are heavier or have a bigger waist (I'm a 31) but still not that tall (sub 5'10") you might consider the Large - Short version.
review.name: Great Bibs for every day

review.reviewBody:
Bought these in October 2022. I’m 5’9” 205lbs athletic build , big thighs wide shoulders. The mediums were restrictive so I got the large regular. Have the straps up about as far as they will go for length but otherwise fit well. 
Wore them all season, very waterproof and they seemed to be as advertised. While cleaning at the end of the season I noticed a hole on the inside of right knee around the thigh zipper. It had worn through. My last ski pants lasted 10 years. In 50+ years of skiing I’ve NEVER worn through a pair of ski pants, especially within 6mos. Don’t know if it’s a design flaw or what but it wore through were the zipper is welded to pant material. For the cost I’d expect the durability to match the description. Wouldn’t buy again. Disappointed ☹️
review.name: Doesn’t live up to the hype

review.reviewBody: These are by far the best pant or bib I have ever owned (a long list that includes allot of top brands). The fit is perfect thanks to way they adjust (I am 6'2 and kinda skinny and a size M fits like a dream). These have kept me warm and dry all season long. So far they have been extremely durable. I see why these have such a rep and a cult following.
review.name: Absolute Rockstar

review.reviewBody:
Good: Unit works perfect for a small propane grill.
Bad: Quality is poor. I keep my woodwind smoker and grill box covered on my porch.  I use the grill box probably 35-40 times per year.  However, the inside has rusted out within 2 years.  On year 3 the joints on the back are rusted beyond repair.  I've already replaced the cast iron grate as well.
review.name: Rusts out quickly even covered

review.reviewBody: I purchased. BB30 BBQ for my Pro 60 14” stove. After purchase I found that the BBQ would not close completely with the pizza stone inserted in the BBQ. The two tabs that secure the BBQ grate during transport provide an interference with the pizza stone. Without modification of the tabs, these two items are not compatible with one another. The modification was simple for me and I am now happy with my purchase, but not all buyers will have the ability to make them work together. Buyer beware. Camp Chef has been a part of my family for forty years - this is the first issue I have had with three stoves and many accessories.
review.name: BB30 BBQ accessory & COPS pizza stone

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I like the grill box, and the option to add smoker pellets underneath, and the thermometer. However, I have the expedition 14, and when you open the grill box, it hits the back shield of the stove. So you have to hold it open the whole time. It doesn’t stay open by itself. Which is a bit of a safety hazard and makes cooking a lot more difficult.
review.name: Grill box: great, but design flaw

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] great addition to our three burner Camp Chef Explorer
review.name: stainless grill box

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] The grill box worked perfectly on my Sidekick. The temperature got to 500 degrees quickly and seared the steak on the cast iron grates. Loving my purchase and makes my pellet grill much more versatile.
review.name: Loving the Grill Box

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I like the grill box. But it has hot and cold spots. You will need to move food around on the grill to get food to come off the grill at the same time
review.name: Cooks unevenly

review.reviewBody:
Initially I hated this bbq box and I told Camp Chef just that.  They tried to be helpful but in the end it was more about figuring out now to make it work for me.  It does not work like a regular gas/charcoal grill.  Used as is the fat will collect on the slanted bottom and roll to the back then cause non stop flare ups.  I tried covering in tin foil but that really created a problem.  I was going to junk it then happened to try wood chips in perforated tin foil in the bottom of the box - whoa! huge difference.  Make the chip packet the size of the unlouvered section in the bottom and let the start smoking before cooking whatever it is - now you have the convenience of a gas grill and the taste of a wood/charcoal fire.  It also minimizes the flare ups until the chips catch fire which isn't a problem.  The intensity of the fire will determine how quick the flare up happens and how bad it is. 

The cast iron grate is heavy duty and very good quality as is the rest of the bbq box.  Clean up is a breeze - just pull the grate off, pull the bbq box off the cooktop then go clean out the bottom and dump it out.  With the wood packets the bottom doesn't really get too bad.  It takes a bit to get familiar with what temps give you the right result on different cuts of meat but I haven't ruined anything yet vs it has turned out a lot of fantastic food.  I use the 14" single burner because there is just 2 of us.  I sometimes wish for a larger surface (2 burner) but that's a lot of weight and a lot of wasted space so make the single burner work.  Liked it so much I now have two cookers, 2 bbq boxes, 2 griddles, carrying cases, covers and two woks to use on them.  Very good  bbq box after some time to figure it out.
review.name: Very good bbq box once you figure it out

review.reviewBody: Have used for years paired with single griddle plate. It is unlimited what you can cook on it for two people. Steak, Hash brown patties, hamburgers, biscuits for biscuits and gravy, chicken, and pretty much anything that you cook on a regular grill. It is just a little smaller.
review.name: Outstanding addition to our 14inch two burner

review.reviewBody: Description says, “instantly vaporizes grease drippings”. Think how that actually works… I think this grilled is a flawed design. The actual grill and hot plate are so close together compared to a regular gas grill. So when you cook anything with a fat content and it drips down it immediately becomes a grease fire. Not a big deal on normal grill, but since there really is no space the flames engulf your food. Also, doesn’t help to close the lid to put out grease fire because too much airflow. If you keep to chicken breast and vegetables works great.
review.name: Grease Fire

review.reviewBody: Great product! Great quality! Great service! Love Camp Chef!
review.name: Outstanding quality

Patagonia fleece vest excellence!
Perfect fitment! Very classy look!
Perfect for fall!
Very fair price and super fast shipping!
Back Country is one of the best!

review.reviewBody: I bought this as a gift for my son in Oar Tan. He was ecstatic and said that all the Finance Majors were wearing this vest. Fits like a normal Large. Looks great with a button up shirt. Great price as compared to other stores.
review.name: Awesome vest! Oar tan

review.reviewBody: I received the item as a gift. The gift event is beyond the return window. The item is nowhere near the color shown!!! It is a very reddish/pinkish brown. This is obviously a Patagonia "second".  I have dealt in fabrics and coatings for decades and understand color hues very well. The color that I received is obviously a MISTAKE. Shame on Backcountry for the bait and switch. Hopefully, someone at the homeless shelter will use it.
review.name: Won't let me rate it ZERO stars!!!!

review.reviewBody: Nice material versus my regular fleece vests, great for wearing about town or off in the woods.  I found it just about the right amount of warmet to be very versatile, just throw a sweater on underneath when the termperature dips.  Size runs pretty roomy, I'd advise ordering true to size as it leaves a of bit space for layering.
review.name: Patagonia "Best" Vest

review.reviewBody:
For the price this vest should not pill this much.
I did not expect this from Patagonia.
review.name: Excesive pilling

review.reviewBody: I ordered and received two Patagonia vests to add to several I owned (purchased previously from other vendors), all size small.  One, in brown, was fine, and it fit identically to my previous items.  The second (purple) was stretched out of shape and was larger in fit, especially at arm holes and waist.  The presence of a tied on tag, along with the condition of the item, led me to suspect that it had previously been worn.  Therefore, I do not recommend Backcountry, and I will not purchase from this vendor in the future.
review.name: Patagonia better sweater vest, mens

review.name: Very nice. Bit expensive

review.reviewBody: This is a great down vest! I have had other brands but this is my favorite. Love how the down is ethically sourced. 6' 190lbs Large fits perfect
review.name: Warm

review.reviewBody:
Purchased as a more durable vest(fabric wise) compared to a Patagonia Down Sweater vest. Styling caught my eye, as all Patagonia puffies tend to look alike. Probably not quite as warm as Down Sweater vest due to lower fill power, but fabric feels more durable and the pockets have a soft feel fabric lining (vest feels warm enough for my needs). 
Zipper is typical Euro (zips on opposite side...not a problem). Also like that it is a 2-way zip, though the top slider fits in the teeth (elements) a bit loose, so will have to see how that hold up in the long run. 
Definitively recommend it, unless you have a large phone and want to fit it in your chest (flap ) pocket (max height of phone is 5 3/4" if you want to snap the flap).
review.name: Great looking Vest with good warmth

review.reviewBody: I really do like the chest pocket. It holds a iPhone XR well. This vest does not have any internal pockets but I don?t miss them as the chest pocket feels like it functions better for me. I feel the weight of the phone in other jacket?s inside pockets. It is perfect for cool fall days in Michigan (hoodie underneath). The ?Dusk? color is more blue than I thought. I was expecting more of a gray tone. I do like the color but if you are dead set on gray, it really isn?t.  Construction seems solid.  I think this will be in heavy use.
review.name: Chest Pocket is Nice

review.reviewBody: Great boot. I live at 9,000 ft in a mountain town. I wanted good winter boots that I can slip on and run to my car and walk to work. Like them so much that I have been wearing around town and using them as my fatbiking boots now too. Usually a 10 wide and the 9 fit pretty well!
review.name: Great boot for all purposes

review.reviewBody: These boots seem to be very good quality. I was surprised at how comfortable they were as they are tall kind of heavy boots. I have worn a size 10 for many years but as of late that size in most shoes is a little tight. These size 10s were if anything a little loose but comfy. I wore them for the first time today on a 3 mile walk through muddy woods and they did not shafe or rub. They are in fact a little bouncy and put a bit of spring in my step. So far so good!
review.name: Comfy, dry and warm.

review.reviewBody: I've had many winter boots but none as good as Bogs Bozeman. The slip in slip off makes them convenient carry gear or kids. Waterproof is great for warm snow but the insulation can't be beat for days under 10 degrees. I literally wear these from dec-March but this winter it's Nov-April. I've even taken them elk hunting in thigh high snow when my winter hunting boots were too thin to keep the cold out for a full day in the woods.
review.name: Wear them all winter

review.reviewBody: Excellent boots... really like them!! Very comfortable to wear all day.
review.name: Comfortable!!!

review.reviewBody:
I think I've used this 3-4 times so far.  The use case is Jan-Mar (northern hemisphere), max of 4 nights and 5 days.  I guess you could go longer depending on details.  I put a western mountaineering Kodiak in a compression sack, tent and clothes intending on the weather being between -5F and 30F ideally.  All my junk fits wel but it forces you to think more about what you'll need. Last time going up Whitney and having to walk a good portion of the road to the trail head (as the road isn't maintained in the winter, you can't drive all the way to the trail head usually) I wore light boots on the road until I got to the the steeper and deeper snow where I swapped to the la sportiva nepal cubes and cramp ons I had tied to the sides of the pack.  I guess I'm saying it's versatile, and I was really happy on the way down I didn't have to do the last couple of miles on the road in the Cubes (they are terrible to walk on pavement in).
Before having this pack I was winging it with a 3 season backpack but kept tearing and damaging it with ice axes and a shovel.  Like most people I went into analysis paralysis and ddecided the money for dynema wasn't worth it, as this is a pretty light pack already.
review.name: No complaints

review.reviewBody:
I took this pack on a 3-day (guided) climb of Mount Baker. Most guide services suggest an obscenely large pack size for such a short trip (e.g. 65-75 L). However, by choosing gear wisely and packing carefully (watch videos on how to pack a climbing pack) I was easily able to fit all my clothing, gear, shared gear, and food for this trip, with even a bit of room to spare. A larger pack would have been not only overkill, but probably induced me to bring more useless stuff!

The design is very thoughtful, from the removable top, to the mesh helmet net. The side pockets are sized to fit wands or snow pickets, and _not_ water bottles. There are load-tightening straps, and places to secure your ice axe or ice tools, as well as crampons, but that's it -- and that's a good thing. This pack helps you minimize "danglies" while still offering essential tiedown points.

Overall, I gladly recommend this for 2-4 day alpine climbing/touring/skiing trips in Summer; perhaps 1-3 days in Winter.
review.name: Outstanding alpine pack

review.reviewBody:
Have used this pack a few times for fun but recently used it for an overnight SAR training mission here in CO.  Wore it for around 12 straight hours and 10 miles of hiking, lots of vert while carrying a litter etc with a 35lb winter loadout, full volume.

Back does get sweaty af even at 25 degrees at night with just a base layer but I somewhat expected that given the design.

Padding is very minimal but somehow handles 35 lbs of gear very comfortably and could probably go up to 50 which is stellar for this light of a pack.  Load is very stable and moves with my body extremely well.  Will test out the ski and ice axe carry soon.  Material seems durable.  Simple pack but has everything I’ve needed so far.  Helmet “net” is perfect.

I have the smaller Mutant as well (also great) but would really like one around 75 liters for carrying additional winter and tech gear.

Insanely good pack for the money.
review.name: Excellent winter SAR pack

review.reviewBody: I used it for backcountry skiing the fit and how it proformed when skinning or skiing excellent. Its only top accessible, and a lack of easy acces pocket for avalanche equipment. Note I knew it wasn't a dedicated ski pack wanted something larger then what was available. Was able to comfortably carry and ski with heavier loads. I enjoyed 50 days of skiing something like 35 of them were backcountry here in Alaska. Skiing adventures from Hatcher pass ,with lots of local runs near Anchorage , and some trips to Turnagain pass.
review.name: Skiing with technical climbing pack

review.reviewBody: I don?t alpine climb but I bought this pack because of all the features and they all actually held up. I can throw my whole rack in my bag with a 70m rope on top and it comfortable with all the adjustments to the pack and I only have the 38L. With sport climbing I use the ice axe straps to hold my extendable stick clip. Another bonus with it being a alpine pack it?s pretty water proof. I got stuck in a couple of thunderstorms over a weekend and everything was soaked except what was in my pack. My rope and gear were dry inside. My only request would be for the rain top to be removable for lighter treks and easier access. Other than that 10/10 would recommend for and climber alpine or not
review.name: Love it for cragging

review.reviewBody:
I bought this pack AFTER I'd purchased its smaller sibling the Mutant 38. I was so impressed by how focused the pack was on durability and purpose. The shoulder straps feel great once the pack has weight in it, the hip belt with loops is really useful, especially if you're moving with a lot of gear or need to hook a water bottle somewhere. I like that the 52 has "picket pockets" that you can use to hold anything from tent poles to pickets. 

I initially bought the 38 for shorter trips into the rockies with a day's worth of climbing gear and supplies but as time went by my objective became more time-intensive so I bought the 52 to carry 3 days of food and supplies along with my trad kit. I do appreciate that you can strip the pack down, although if you're going up on a rope I don't think I'd strip the pack down and use it on climbing routes unless you're moving for days on end, such as completing a cirque or traversing a range. If you're on a single day trad route, I'd bring a much smaller pack like a cotopaxi luzon that would double as a stuff sack. 

I like that the pack keeps the weight centered, how narrow it is at your hips to accommodate a harness, and how durable it is. I plan on using the 38 in the Rockies but the 52 is part of my kit for a longer trip in Gates of the Arctic that will keep me away from our base camp for 3-4 days at a time. 

My only suggestion is to include shock cord or something elastic on the front of the pack. I see a lot of people talk about avy gear and it makes sense to have a pack that lets you carry a shovel, but this is a climbing and mountaineering pack and something to secure crampons with would be a way better addition than a place for a shovel. Just my thoughts.
review.name: Excellent mid-range mountain pack

review.reviewBody: These gloves were impossible to get on.  They run really small.  So I can't say how they would perform.
review.name: Runs really small

review.reviewBody: Full disclosure that I got these too late in the year for mountain bike season, and have been using them for nordic skiing instead. My only complaint with them is that the fit is just a bit weird - the fingers are way longer than my Giro DND gloves, and the material doesn't have as much stretch, so it does feel a bit tight around the fingers. I was a little worried that they would be too tight, but once I'm moving I don't notice it at all. The screen compatibility takes a little bit of careful tapping since the fingertips are long on me, but it works pretty well ? about what I would expect from most gloves. The grip on the palm feels really solid. I also really like the wrist cuffs on these - they're plenty snug & come down a good ways on my wrist, so I don't have to worry about getting hit with wind if my sleeves ride up a bit. Lastly, since I've been XC skiing in these, I've gotten to test them in some prettttyyy gnarly conditions. Today was about 20F, with quite a bit of wind whipping around, and I was really impressed with how warm my hands were. I even crash landed into a snowbank, and they held up super well to that, considering how dang thin they are. They're definitely not 100% water proof, but if you're a clown that sometimes goes hands-first into the snow, they'll keep ya going out there.
review.name: Survived The Ol' Snow Dunking Test

review.itemreviewed: Quest Element GTX Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody:
I have a pair of Salomon hiking boots that I bought over 10 years ago. They are still good but I’m travelling to the UK in October so I thought I’d buy a new pair. Wore them a few times to use them before long walks.
quite confortable, very stable and solid feeling on the ground, very large compared to my old boots but I wear orthotics so it’s a good thing but could feel too loose for some people with a thin foot.Chaffed my ankle on one side, wore thicker socks hopefully that problem will resolve itself  with time. real test will be hiking in the Scottish Highlands later this fall..
review.name: Foot feels very stable

review.itemreviewed: Quest Element GTX Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody:
Bought in Oct 2022, loved them... super comfy, supportive, grippy and kept my feet dry through boggy areas.
However, now at the end of my second walking holiday (with occasional use at home) and the soles of my feet ache, the soles have worn and no longer feel cushioned and can feel rocks through the sole. Bit disappointed as have previously used salomons due to the comfort and durability.
review.name: Comfy supportive and grippy

review.itemreviewed: Quest Element GTX Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: I bought these for my wife, after explaining to her that Salomon’s is what I wore while in the military. She wore them to her job at a “range” that she is an instructor at , and she fell I. Love with the comfort and quality
review.name: Great boot, great vomfort

review.itemreviewed: Quest Element GTX Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody:
I love these boots in every way except how they hurt an inch to 2 inches above my ankle. I don't know what it is...tieing the boots looser helps but doesn't fix the issue. The boots left a red abrasion after a mile hike on very uneven ground (didn't bruise though). I will say, they are waterproof! I walked through low flow rivers (about an inch to 2 inches in depth) without an issue! 

As far as slipping goes, I've only slipped on a wet log so far (I caught myself). I have gone free bouldering and hiked through mud/rivers. Great experiences! I felt like I had great footholds even with the smooth granite rock. 

8/10 would recommend with 2 points taken away for the upper ankle pain. 

I got an 8.5 and I'm normally an 8. My heels aren't slipping at all but I still have room for warm socks.
review.name: Great! Waterproof (to a point)! But ouch

review.itemreviewed: Quest Element GTX Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: Love the way these boots feel. Very supportive, grippy soles, generous toe box. I did need to break them in a bit, but it didn't take long. Colors match the photos and I found these to be true to size. 10/10
review.name: Amazing

review.itemreviewed: Quest Element GTX Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: Fourth pair of Salomon walking boots…… never disappointed!
review.name: Truly excellent

review.itemreviewed: Quest Element GTX Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: I bought this same model about 9 years ago and they were the best boots I've ever had.  I had to throw them away because they started smelling so bad from being wet all the time.  This new version is harder to break it, and so far the crease across my toes is still quite sharp, and the top edge of the right boot is sharp and left an abrasion above my ankle after 1/2 a mile.  I like how they are roomy enough for different sock thickness and the lug is awesome.  If you buy these make sure you give yourself plenty of miles to break them in.
review.name: Not as good as the last version I had

review.reviewBody:
I bought these because Backcountry's description said they are polarized, and before purchasing them I online-chatted with a Backcountry rep who said they are polarized. But they are not. According to Oakley's website, the Oakley canteen 0009225-12 have "Plutonite lenses provide 100 percent UV filtering". Apparently the Dark Bronze Lenses are NOT polarized. Oakley offers two other lens options for the Canteen model that are polarized: Chrome Iridium Polarized Lenses and Jade Iridium Polarized Lenses. But again, the dark bronze lenses are not polarized. No wonder they're at least 25 dollars cheaper!

review.reviewBody:
My dad has Parkinson’s, which has severely impacted his mobility and motor skills in the last year, and with the colder months approaching, he was frustrated with typical down blankets that were heavy, bulky and hard for him to maneuver, particularly after a traumatic fall where he broke 9 ribs. 😭
I was scouring everywhere for the lightest but warmest blanket I could find  that was no bigger than a full-size; then, I woke up in the middle of the night: camping blanket!! 
Within minutes, I found reviews for this blanket. I immediately bought it and had it sent to his house. My dad has been using it for a month and has loved it from the second he got it. (But, I was pretty sure he was just saying he liked it because he didn’t want to disappoint me.) 
I finally got to visit him, and I just felt this amazing blanket for myself and wooowww It is lofty & luxurious without feeling heavy at all.
 I was worried the nylon fabric would be slick and slide everywhere, but it isn’t at all. It doesn’t feel overly-utilitarian or “camp-gear” like at all. 
The fact you can pin a sheet to it so you only have to wash the sheet- GENIUS!!! WHO IS THE DESIGNER FOR THIS BLANKET GIVE THEM A RAISE.
The fact that it’s water resistant- PERFECT!!
It really exceeded my expectations. 

No, we don’t use it for camping, so I can’t vouch for it in the wild, but I can say that my dad is warm, comfortable, and can get in/out of bed  safely because of it. And although I don’t have the luxury of living close by to help him as much as I’d like- you’ve made me feel like a hero. ❤️
review.name: Lightweight & lofty. Heavenly.

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This is a great rain jacket and can serve as a great outer shell over a fleece in colder weather. At the current price point, this jacket is a very good value.
review.name: I Love This Jacket!

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I had this jacket for about a month now and have used it daily as the outer shell of my rucking (hiking) clothing kit - wicking layer, warmth layer, outer shell. Living in Michigan, I've already had the opportunity to use it through most weather conditions - from cold and snowy, to warm-ish and windy. I've been very happy with it and would recommend it as use as an outer shell, but not an only layer because it's not very breathable. For me, that's not a big deal. When I'm done wearing, I turn it inside-out to let the interior dry out on the back of a chair. Just know, if you're doing physical activity, and this is the only layer against your skin, the sweat it's not going to wick away or evaporate. PRO's: Great wind and rain protection. Lightweight. Easily packable. Roomy side pockets. Good fit. CON's: Breathability (holds perspiration inside). Pricey.
review.name: Great choice as an outer shell

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Since the Venture 1, I have owned 4 more. i have one available everywhere i go. the weather changes often in the south, cool, cold , wet or dry.. the pit zips and light weight make it enormously handy for my lifestyle, work or play.

review.itemreviewed: Experience Wild Trail Running Shoe - Women's
review.reviewBody: Best. Shoe. Ever. Recently got into trail running and purchased these. They were great out of the box and carried me across my first official finish line this weekend. Ordering again.
review.name: About to buy my second pair

review.itemreviewed: Experience Wild Trail Running Shoe - Women's
review.reviewBody: I love to take long walks and hikes but have foot issues of heal shock absorption, sore ball of the foot, and a toe numbness - these Altra Experience Wild felt incredible right away - I love them!
review.name: Love at first wearing!

review.itemreviewed: Experience Wild Trail Running Shoe - Women's
review.reviewBody: I bought for backpacking on the CT. I just finished a few segments, but was backpacking for four days. No hot spots or blisters, just comfort and grip. Laces stay tied without double-knots, I had ample toe room, and they were comfy all day on the trail. They gripped rocks and did well in the mud and on roots. I could not have been happier.
review.name: Excellent shoes for hiking the Colorado Trail

review.itemreviewed: Experience Wild Trail Running Shoe - Women's
review.reviewBody: Loving this pair for day-to-day use, especially as I am on my feet most of the day. I can transition straight to the gym for a long run and it's seamless with these shoes. Love the zero drop and may never run in another brand ever again. I would definitely suggest sizing up a half to a whole size if buying for a running shoe. Great tread for outdoors, so i can't wait to get them out on the trail. Wish i had bought the orange pair too!
review.name: Bought for the trails, but love them so I wear them everyday

review.itemreviewed: Experience Wild Trail Running Shoe - Women's
review.reviewBody: I've been using lone peaks for almost a decade, and these feel so much better for me. I am able to hop around on the trails so much more, and I'm already ordering another pair to add to the collection!
review.name: I love these shoes!!

review.itemreviewed: Experience Wild Trail Running Shoe - Women's
review.reviewBody: I like these shoes: design, color, and how comfortable my toes are, I bought them, but I had to return them as the heel support is too big. Please reduce the size of the heel support to around 2-3 mm. I want these shoes but can't wear them - it's too much pressing from the ankle support. I tried half-size bigger but they were too big and too wide for me. I am sad that I had to return them. :((
review.name: No

review.itemreviewed: Experience Wild Trail Running Shoe - Women's
review.reviewBody: I was so disappointed as I looked forward to these for a while . The support in the heel is too much and your ankles don't feel supported especially on trails with uneven surfaces . I didn't feel locked to the ground while putting in a few trail miles to test them out . So back to the drawing board in a trail shoe for me .
review.name: Honestly , not what I expected at all .

review.itemreviewed: Experience Wild Trail Running Shoe - Women's
review.reviewBody: The fit of these shoes were not terrible. They had good support and quality. I did return because they felt a little tight in the heels. My main complaint is their terrible customer service. I returned these shoes over 4 weeks ago and have not received a refund. It's been two weeks since I emailed customer care about it with no response and there's never anyone available on the chat services. I don't even know why they have it. It feels like I'm communicating with a ghost town and I'd just like my money back for these rather expensive shoes.
review.name: Tight in the heels- terrible customer service

review.itemreviewed: Experience Wild Trail Running Shoe - Women's
review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I received these complimentary in exchange for my honest review. I haaaaate wearing gym shoes across the board but these are fairly comfortable! They are a bit too narrow for my feet, I noticed some pressure after wearing them for several hours. These definitely seemed to help with the impact on my injured knee. Would recommend!
review.name: Comfortable, cute

review.itemreviewed: Experience Wild Trail Running Shoe - Women's
review.reviewBody: I love the fact that these are off trail shoes and that's why I bought them. Was hoping they were somewhat similar and comfort to the women's forward, and the they do well on trails, the shape of these is just different enough to where they don't fit quite right. The toebox rubs even though I went up a half size larger than I normally wear. And I just feel like going up another half size would make the heel slip too much.
review.name: Really wanted to love them

name: Experience Wild Trail Running Shoe - Women's

review.reviewBody: I was looking for a super lightweight jacket to travel with to protect for light rain, wind or chilly weather. The Houdini is perfect for this. It packs very small in its own pocket and it came in handy a number of times when it started drizzling or raining or it got a bit cold at night. The hood was good, the fit was good. I suspect it doesn't breathe all that well, but that was ok because it kept me warm when it got a bit chilly. I'm fairly sure that I would overheat in it if I tried to hike in it. I would also not use this for any type of serious weather or cold. It's very, very thin but it is perfect for its purpose.
review.name: Perfect lightweight jacket

review.reviewBody:
This is thing is good for stopping the wind, but you better be standing still watching a soccer game or something because there's only 5 Cubic Feet Per Minute (CFM) of breath-ability in this jacket fabric. For comparison, 35 CFM is recommend for backpacking and 70CFM for high output activity such as cross country skiing.

Why do companies like Patagonia and Arcteryx do this? Because high breath-ability fabrics wear out sooner (because they're uncalendered) and they simply don't want the early returns from customers that don't understand what's going on.
review.name: It does NOT breathe

review.reviewBody: This is the greatest lightweight shell jacket ever.  The colors are great too.  Highly recommend.  I own multiple colors.
review.name: Best lightweight jacket

review.reviewBody:
If I have to pay full price, I will definitely return.
Superior light weight, superior windbreaker, and pretty good protection from light showers rain. But this jacket trapped sweat inside the jacket. I got wet clothes after running.
review.name: Not bad jacket

review.reviewBody: Awesome windbreaker for running and light rain. Not waterproof though .love the small cinches and packs down small and light,

review.reviewBody: Super light wait and packable. had to size up to an XL to wear anything more than T-shirt under it and to get the length I need in the arms. looking forward to using it.

review.reviewBody:
Great little jacket. I just wanted something for mountain biking that would take the bite off my skin at the beginning of a ride but could also fit in my pocket or a frame bag once I warmed up. It is perfect for that and I also find it to be comfortable to just wear around town or on my way to work. The wind protection it offers makes up for lightweight fleece's warmth and it is way lighter - not to mention that I can put this on over long sleeves and it slides ride over whatever I'm wearing under it. I hate when jacket sleeves stick to your base layers and bunch everything up. I did size up to a large just to give better range of motion while on the bike since it is not a stretchy material. I am 5' 9.5" and would typically wear a medium if I was just hiking with it, but it still fits well and doesn't fit like a trash sack the way some of these jackets can be. 

My only complaint about it is that the cinch system on the drawstring, while being very minimal, does not function well and you will end up fiddling with it if you need to use it. Basically there are two tiny notches that each bungee strand hooks into and holds it snug enough be able to cinch down, but on the waist every time I pull the strings they pop out of the little notches and then I have to feed them back into the notches and very carefully cinch it down without popping them out again. The hood uses the same thing and for some reason works fine so they are probably just not a super consistent mechanism.
review.name: Does what its supposed to... Mostly.

review.reviewBody:
Solid work from a solid company. 
This jacket is super light? great as an add to a backcountry pack. Does well in a light rain, not going to keep you dry through a downpour? at all. Good end breaker and super light. Exactly what you would expect.
review.name: Exactly as adver

review.reviewBody: I bought this for my son for a gift as he recently lost a lightweight Patagonia jacket. By the description, it says it is a jacket. It weighs less than 6 ounces in the packaging. I am so disappointed and would have been so embarrassed to give it to him. Now I need a more appropriate gift. I hope that I can find one.

review.reviewBody:
Hands down the best rear tire I've ever run...I've run every single Maxxis tire.

I run the Aggressor on the rear on two different bikes:
- 27.5" Kona Process 153 CR/DL [2.5 WT]
- 29" Kona Honzo CR/DL [2.3 WT].

The Aggressor works well in many trail conditions, with the exception of mud. To my eye it's more of a squared off tire profile that grips well but also rolls well. Works great for me in off camber root situations where the rear tire wants to slide off/wash out, rips berms, never breaks loose under the stress of hard climbs.

Assegai or DHF in the front, Aggressor in the rear!
review.name: The best rear tire I've ever run!

review.reviewBody: I got the 2.5 3C MaxGrip version for the rear tire on my Ibis HD4.  Most people with Ibis bikes are familiar with the "rock grinder" effect of the rear suspension layout.  I live in South Lake Tahoe and ride a lot of sandy/pebble filled trails.  The tightly packed knobs (especially the ones with the center cutout) grab small pebbles and throw them against the seat tube and into the "rock grinder."  I found the smaller knobs also tended to squirm more than the Minion DHF that I'm used to.  Rear traction getting up rock ledges was also better with the minion.  I guess these are heavy due to the tread pattern, but offered no advantage that I could see (maybe wear time?).  Going back to the DHF front and rear.
review.name: Better options from Maxxis

review.reviewBody:
There's so much to love about these shorts. The tiger lily/taupe color is definitely a head turner, the fabric is soft and stretchy, the cut is flattering, and the length goes far enough down your thighs that you don't have to worry about your cheeks hanging out.

Beware that the fit is MID RISE (NOT high-waisted), which wasn't specified in the description. I first wore them with a crop top and was quickly humbled as the shorts sit below the narrowest part of your waist and look strange with an exposed midriff. I'll only be wearing them with full length tops.
review.name: Head-turning shorts

review.reviewBody:
As a female mountain biker with thick thighs and smaller waist, these shorts are PERFECT! I am 5"4 on a good day and am 150 lbs, built like a gymnast; and bought a size 8. I have short legs and finding shorts that I'm not constantly pulling down or just look like capris on me has been insanely difficult. 

These will look great out on the town and on the bike - they have enough room for a thin chamois. Super stoked and bought the green and black pair. Hoping they'll come back with something similar if not the same because I need every color!
review.name: Finally Found the Holy Grail of Shorts

review.reviewBody: For 98% cotton and only 2% spandex I expected these shorts to run on the stiff side, but they have great stretch. I'm typically a size 6 and sometimes a size 8 but would definitely recommend sizing up if you want a looser fit. I could've gone with a size 10 and been happy, but due to the fabric I imagine it will stretch with more use. I'm excited to wear these all summer!
review.name: Comfy and cute

review.reviewBody: I bought these last year and was absolutely thrilled with them. I mounted them with tech bindings and used them in the resort two days to get a feel for them then have kept them off the lifts since. I liked them so much on my first day I bought another pair on way home from the slopes for my wife. They have continued to impress from the first day, they are extremely agile and fun to ski. They strike a great balance of light enough, easy to ski, solid float, stability, and predicitbility. They are a blast in trees and bumps, I feel like I can pick any line I want (usually bad ones) and these skis just figure it themselves. I am not the fastest or most powerful skier but it's easy to find their upper limit in rough snow. Ski these with a little left in the reserve tank and you'll have a blast. They are my do it all backcountry ski but if you prefer a lively friendlier ski on the resort and don't mind a little extra weight on the skin track they would make a great 50/50 ski. I got the 173 which is a bit short for my height and weight, this is a decision I am very happy with, I havent wished for more float and don't intend to ski them all out so don't need the extra stability with more length. Use them for what they are meant to be and you will be really happy too.
review.name: I really love these skis!

review.reviewBody: Bought these for day to day ski guiding and personal ski touring in Colorado in the San Juans and RMNP. I mounted these with Dynafit Superlight 150's on the tech binding line.  These skis have been great daily drivers for me. I reach for them over other skis daily because they're predictable, and handle a large variety of conditions well. I've skied everything from breaker crust, to steep couloirs with these and they've managed it all well. For the deepest conditions they're a little short and narrow, for the firmest conditions they're a little wide, but with that said, they handle the largest swatch of conditions of any ski I've owned. Highly recommend for comfortable and fun ski touring. I'm 6'0 175lbs, usually ski 184ish skis in this width. I went with the 181 and they've been great, though I'd like to experiment with mounting them back on the alpine line for better high speed stability compared to the tech line.
review.name: Excellent Daily Driver for Touring

review.reviewBody: I recently purchased these skis after a long debate of what mid fat ski to purchase. I cannot explain how happy I am with my purchase and now have a new favorite pair of skis in my quiver. With the perfect amount of tail rocker, camber, and early rise, these skis absolutely crush so many different ski conditions. I would purchase these ten times over and believe there is not a better mid fat ski for the price on the market.
review.name: Best bag for your buck skis

review.reviewBody: I really couldnt ask for anything more in a ski. I will not be skinning with these but I do boot it. I may be wrong but these seem to be a prototype for a future qst 106. They are softer as much as they are lighter. Im not a hard charger but they handled everything with ease and seemed to show me lines i wouldnt see otherwise. Hard pack, crap, 12" powder, tree turns, yup.
review.name: The skis for me.

review.reviewBody: Amazing skis! This is my favorite BC setup and feels almost as sturdy as a dedicated resort ski.
review.name: Salomon QST echo

review.reviewBody: When I first skied the ECHO 106 I was blown away with how it skied on firm snow...I know, weird for a ski designed to be a bit softer for lighter, deeper snow. When I did get into the softer deeper snow I realized just how special this ski is.  It is super damp and has an incredible flex pattern to float in deeper snow and its able to absorb the bumps in the crud. What really makes this ski, IMO, is how light it is for uphill travel!  Nothing like Salomon, once again, giving an already great ski (QST 106) a twin brother that is better in other conditions. Highly recommend!
review.name: Super backcountry/sidecountry,resort POW ski!

review.reviewBody:
I have using QST 106 for long time. Echo has exact same shape but different stiffness and weight.
If you like qst 106 but prefer more lighter or softer one, that’s for you!
Highly recommend!
review.name: Friendly QST 106

review.reviewBody: I ride the QST Lux earlier version and guardian binding. So I really felt the weight difference and was super happy with the feeling on pow turns. It’s time to change the skies. :)
review.name: Super happy

review.reviewBody: I've got some days on these now and loved them right away.. These are the lightest skis I've ever owned and they ski amazing and not just for their weight category.. So far I've skied about every kind of snow except for deep pow and they ski everything great. light and nimble but able handle speed. Really stoked on these!
review.name: Best lightweight skis I've ever owned

review.reviewBody: The QST Echos are exactly what I've been wanting for years -- a lightweight ski that is easy to push uphill, and far more efficient feeling compared to its partners on the QST line.  Yet, it floats and skis great.  I have yet to ski any variable snow, but it has been such a fun ski to have on our deep Colorado winter.  I haven't touched another set of skis since I got the Echos.  Highly recommend!
review.name: The touring skis Ive been waiting for!

review.reviewBody: I was able to use a mounting bracket that bolts to the rain gutter and bought two extending tent poles to support the outer arms. After I took the the photo I extended the tent material so that it barely touches the ground. The roof covers really cut down the heat inside and the hold well even with rain. We use an on demand water heater and the 14 gallons of water onboard for showers. Sets up and takes down in minutes.

review.reviewBody: The 2 rooms. Room for toilet and dry area and the. A wet area for showering. Also extremely easy to setup and pack away. My one complaint is cover had a small knick in it &amp; it didn’t come with any stickers, haha.
review.name: Seems very nice after initial setup. Will be used on an actual trip shortly.

review.reviewBody: Good experience with double ensuite. Easy to deploy and put away. Awesome fit to my 4Runner
review.name: Ensuite mounted double

review.reviewBody: I have owned this for about 6 months and have used it over 25 times. Great product. Goes up in seconds. Often get a lot of comments and questions about it. I have the double but usually only use one side. Hopefully that will change soon when I get a proper shower. Makes night time bathroom visits simple! I agree with a few of the other reviews. The pull knobs have fallen off a few times, luckily, I have always found them. I really like how it folds up with plenty of space in the cover, this also only takes a minute or so. Overall great product that I get a lot of use from.
review.name: Ensuite

review.reviewBody: We love our double en-suite. We have it mounted on our 22 Jeep Rubicon. It’s so easy and fast to set up and tear down. It’s really nice out on the trail to quickly set up one side for a potty. Absolute game changer for showers. We couldn’t be happier with it. @TheViewFromHereOverland
review.name: Easy set up

review.reviewBody: I’m taking off a star for two reasons. I had to spend about 2hrs modifying the mounting bracket to take larger bolts. Would not have been an issue if the brackets just had holes but since they are slots drilling them out is nearly impossible. But I got them to work. The other down side is that the arms do not stick straight out. They bend down with the weight of the shower. I am able to fix this but most people would not. The height adjustment also is not as easy as they show. I’m still trying to work on a fix for that. Other than that though it was super easy to setup, use, and take down. Worked great on our week long camping trip. Kept my kids from looking like homeless people. I know this sounds more negative than positive but I really do love it.
review.name: One of the best purchases I have made for my Camper Setup

review.reviewBody:
I bought this tee expecting good quality, I was WRONG and here are the reasons:
1.- RUNS SMALL. I usually go for L in all my tees, but these are off size! You have to size up one or even Two sizes. I thought the tees were designed for Swedish people, but I was wrong.
2.- POOR QUALITY. Pilling the first day of use. Thin material. The collar stitching coming off. The shirt is made somewhere in ASIA and apparently with cheap quality material. 

AVOID buying this t shirt. I love this brand and have bought quality products in the past, but this should go out of their catalog, they’re just selling a really cheap product with their logo.
review.name: BAD SIZING + POOR QUALITY

review.reviewBody: Material so thin it was see-through. Runs 1-2 sizes smaller than advertised (XL fit like Medium).Unwearable.
review.name: Poor Quality

review.reviewBody: Could be good but I actively avoid wearing this because they have sewn a tag (product care etc) on the inside along the seam (lands just above hip bone) which is frustratingly itchy.  I cut it as flush as possible without risking damage to the shirt but its not enough, I purchased two of these shirts and neither gets worn.  Also, as far as fit goes, they are short.
review.name: Frustrating

review.reviewBody: Have worn the shirt 4 times and the fit is great.  Not too tight, not too loose.  Time will tell on durability as I’ve only worn it a handful of times so far.
review.name: Great fit

review.reviewBody: Nice assortment of colors, low stated logo and comfortable. I wear a small for other Fjallraven tops but a medium in this t-shirt as I need extra length for tucking it in. My biggest issue is the shirts aren’t long enough. What I like about these shirts are the colors, small well placed logo and feeling.
review.name: Fun colors, nice look and comfortable

review.reviewBody: It’s a great basic tee. The length on the sleeves and the main body is awesome. I wish it was a bit more of a relaxed fit as that’s what I find most comfortable in a tee.
review.name: Excellent Tee

review.reviewBody: This shirt feels and wears like a cotton tee, but performs like synthetic! Because of the 60/40 poly-cotton blend, this shirt is perfect for warmer weather. No frills and no complaints. For size reference, I'm 6 foot 4 in. 190lbs and the size XL fits me perfectly.
review.name: Fantastic Basic Tee

review.reviewBody: Shirt felt great and looked great! I had to buy it despite being a bit too expensive for a normal t shirt in my opinion. I expected some higher quality from Fjällräven. I wore the t shirt on one short hike (under 10 miles) with my usual walking backpack, and the shirt immediately had pilling all across the lower back. I've never had this problem with my backpack for the past 12 years of wearing it, so I suspect it is just a problem with the durability of the t shirt. Quite disappointed and I regret buying this product
review.name: Surprisingly low durability

review.reviewBody: I am starting to notice that all Fjalravens cloths follow a weird sizing. The M is too small, and the L is way too big. If you are like me, stuck in a size between a M & a L, go with L and hopefully it shrinks down after a couple washes to fit.
review.name: Weird Size

review.reviewBody: I loved this t-shirt as soon as I took it out of the packaging. The feel of it is noticeably premium and will be great for everyday use. It's minimal but looks smart, and size M is perfect for me (42" chest). It will be a slow burn because of the high-end price tag, but this is definitely the start of my Fjallraven t-shirt collection.
review.name: The perfect basic t-shirt
